%I A393979 #32 May 01 2026 00:22:43
%S A393979 1,0,0,1,0,1,1,6,9,46,114,478,1394
%N A393979 Number of square-patch-irreducible squarings of a square into n smaller squares, up to dihedral symmetry.
%C A393979 A squaring of order n is a dissection of a square into exactly n smaller squares.
%C A393979 This sequence counts geometric squarings up to the dihedral symmetries of the outer square.
%C A393979 A proper square patch is a union of whole tiles whose union is a square strictly smaller than the outer square.
%C A393979 A squaring is square-patch-reducible if it contains a proper square patch that, after translation, rescaling, and possibly applying a symmetry of the square, is itself a nontrivial squaring.
%C A393979 Otherwise it is square-patch-irreducible.
%C A393979 This is weaker than the classical notion of a simple squared square or squared rectangle, which forbids proper rectangular subpatches as well as proper square subpatches.
%C A393979 For n <= 11 this classification is exhaustive, because all squarings up to symmetry are known exactly in that range, and every proper square patch in an order-n squaring has smaller order < n.
%C A393979 For n <= 11, a(n) equals the number of squarings of order n, up to symmetry, that are square-patch-irreducible; that is, they contain no proper square patch congruent, after rescaling, to a nontrivial smaller squaring.
%C A393979 Empirically, for n = 1..11, a(n) = A221841(n) - r(n), where r(n) is the number of square-patch-reducible squarings of order n up to symmetry.
%H A393979 Stuart Anderson, <a href="https://www.squaring.net/sq/sr/sisr/sisr.html">Simple Imperfect Squared Rectangles</a>.
%H A393979 R. L. Brooks, C. A. B. Smith, A. H. Stone and W. T. Tutte, <a href="https://carlo-hamalainen.net/stuff/Brooks,%20Smith,%20Stone,%20Tutte%20-%20The%20dissection%20of%20rectangles%20into%20squares%20%281940%29.pdf">The dissection of rectangles into squares</a>, Duke Math. J. 7 (1940), 312-340.
%e A393979 a(4)=1 because the unique order-4 squaring has no proper square patch that is itself, after rescaling, a nontrivial smaller squaring.
%e A393979 a(8)=6 because all 6 squarings of order 8 are square-patch-irreducible.
%e A393979 a(9)=9 because 9 of the 16 squarings of order 9 are square-patch-irreducible.
%e A393979 a(11)=114 because 114 of the 183 squarings of order 11 are square-patch-irreducible.
%Y A393979 Cf. A221841, A221842.
%K A393979 nonn,hard,more,new
%O A393979 1,8
